    Date: Fri, 15 Apr 88 12:17:10 EDT
    From: Philip Prindeville [CC]  &lt;philipp@Larry.McRCIM.McGill.EDU&gt;

    My guess is that the motivation for requiring "standard" values for
    host and O/S was so people would put "UNIX" as the O/S instead of
    "SunOS", "Dynix", "Xenix", "UTS", etc.  Just saying "UNIX" gives you
    a good idea of what the foreign file system looks like...

Too bad that hasn't stopped people from using things like "Xenix".  The
following data is from a November snarfing of the MIT.EDU zone via zone
transfer, which contains some 1100 HINFO records.

Unix-like operating systems that aren't "UNIX":
	2 systems running	AIX
	1			HPUX
	1			MINI-UNIX
	25			MINIUNIX
	4			SYSTEM-V
	1			ULTRIX
	3			XENIX
	9			XX
	2			XXX
	1			VENIX

VMS-like:
	29			VMS
	12			VAX/VMS

Kinetics apparently has three operating systems:
	5			CAP
	1			KFPS-1
	1			KIP

In addition to the 21 boxes running CGW (C-GateWay) there is one running "JNC/CGW"

In addition to the 105 boxes running DOS, 5 run MS-DOS.

There's also 18 boxes running "RESERVED".  10 of them are APPLEs and 8
are SUNs.

--------------------
In the less important dimension, there isn't very much standardization
in the CPU type either.  These numbers are only from those machines that
aren't running "UNIX" -- sorry.

IBM PC's of various types.  In addition to
	41 cpus of type	IBM-AT
and	33		IBM-XT
there are
	22		IBMPC
	2		IBM-PC
	3		IBM-PC-AT
	2		IBM-PC-XT
	2		IBMXT
	2		ATCLONE
and 1 each of PC/XT, AT-CLONE, IBM-PC-AT, IBM-PC/AT, IBM-PCXT,
IBM-RC/AT, IBM-RT-PC and IBMPC-AT.

In addition to a variety of VAX-11/730, VAX-11/750, and VAX-11/780 there
is a VAX11/750.  There's also a variety of MICROVAX, MICROVAX-II,
VAXSTATION, VAXSTATION-II and VAXSTATIONS (yes, plural).

